<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Shakuhachi.jpg" class="image" title="A shakuhachi flute, blowing edge up. Left - top view, four holes. Right - bottom view, fifth hole."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Shakuhachi.jpg/200px-Shakuhachi.jpg" width="200" height="341" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Shakuhachi.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A <b>shakuhachi</b> flute, blowing edge up.
<ul>
<li>Left - top view, four holes.</li>
<li>Right - bottom view, fifth hole.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>shakuhachi</b> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja"><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%B0%BA%E5%85%AB" class="extiw" title="wikt:尺八">尺八</a> (しゃくはち)</span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>, <small>IPA</small>:&#160;<span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[ɕakɯhatɕi]</a></span>)</span> is a <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japanese</a> <a href="/wiki/End-blown_flute" title="End-blown flute">end-blown</a> <a href="/wiki/Flute" title="Flute">flute</a>. Its name means "1.8 feet", referring to its size. It is traditionally made of <a href="/wiki/Bamboo" title="Bamboo">bamboo</a>, but versions now exist in wood and plastic. It was used by the monks of the <a href="/wiki/Fuke_Zen" title="Fuke Zen">Fuke school</a> of <a href="/wiki/Zen" title="Zen">Zen</a> <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhism</a> in the practice of <i><a href="/wiki/Suizen" title="Suizen">suizen</a></i> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja"><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%90%B9%E7%A6%85" class="extiw" title="wikt:吹禅">吹禅</a></span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>, blowing meditation)</span>. Its soulful sound made it popular in Western 1980s <a href="/wiki/Pop_music" title="Pop music">pop music</a>.</p>
<p>They are often made in the <a href="/wiki/Pentatonic_scale#Minor_pentatonic_scale" title="Pentatonic scale">minor pentatonic scale</a>.</p>
